**Our aligned Games Industry Strategic Priorities**  
The industry strategic priorities for Games are: Player Centric Experience, Build Great Games, Ensure Efficient Business Operations.  Within each of these objectives there are a series of important business objectives. The rest of this document will outline and define the priorities and call out the top one or two use cases for each objective.

**Our Standard Data Flow and Reference Architecture**

# Strategic Priority: Player Centric Experience {#strategic-priority:-player-centric-experience}

Understanding and catering to the player is the best way for a game company to grow their business and, consequently, is where they spend the majority of their time with data and analysis.  Without players there are no games or business to operate.

**Why Change**  
The industry continues to explode with content. While the playerbase, as a whole, is increasing year over year, particularly within the mobile games market, it is not growing fast enough to address the growth goals of our customers. Recent changes to Cookies and Tracking capabilities on mobile devices have also caused the cost of user acquisition (UA) to explode. Anecdotally we hear customers say that CPI and CPA costs have grown by double to quadruple. In addition to this, however, the quality of acquisition has declined as game developers and publishers have less control and insight into the players they acquire. To continue to grow wallet share for their players, game companies are relying more heavily on post-download sales like Battle Passes, MTX/IAP (MicroTransaction, In App Purchases) and AdMon (Advertising Monetization). The success of these monetization methods has a direct correlation to the amount of time a player spends within the game.

The challenge is everyone is seeking to grow wallet share through similar mechanisms, customer wallets are not increasing in size nor are there more hours in the day to play more games. This competition makes it harder to attract and acquire new players. It also makes it harder to keep players engaged over time as there’s always some new shiny thing out there taking their attention. Add to this the number of free to play titles creating low trial costs for players and retention is harder than it ever has been. As a result, game companies have to innovate and personalize their experiences to maximize player engagement and, as a result, increase their ongoing monetization of the player. 

As a whole monetization is directly correlated to time spent in game (e.g. hours/week), total population playing and how long (days/weeks/months) they have played. The more often a player plays, the more they will monetize. Kabam found with Marvel's Conquest of Champions that the difference in monetization between a player that played 1 day vs 6 days was 2.5X.  A player who played every day of the week was found to be worth at least 5X more than one that played once a week. 

Monetization can also take a lot of time. For a game like Design Home (by GLU Mobile) it might take 60+ days for a player to make their first purchase. If a player churns before that happens then they’ve been a drain on the company. 

**Why Now**  
With so much content out there game companies have very few opportunities to cut through the noise, hook a player and keep them engaged.  It is much more cost effective to focus on engagement and retention strategies than it is to acquire and replace churned players. For most games the largest influx of players will be the day/week of global launch. This is their single opportunity for success. This is also when the majority of the marketing budget is allocated and when your highest Lifetime Value (LTV) players will start playing.  Succeed and you have the opportunity to create a billion dollar franchise, fail and you could lose years of development and your full investment. For this reason you’ll see larger studios, not unlike how VCs operate, running a large number of projects with smaller teams trying to find something they think will resonate with an audience. As these projects progress, reach different milestones, or are moving slower than they should be, you’ll see projects get cancelled. We recently saw this with SIE (Sony Interactive Entertainment) announcing the cancellation of several live service projects after the failure of Concord. 

**Business Executives**

* **Chief Revenue Officer (CRO):** Responsible for revenue across all game titles and, typically, responsible for the User Acquisition budget.  
* **Chief Executive Officer (CEO):** Concerned with yields of titles and their success over time.  
* **Chief Marketing Officer (CMO):** Responsible for brand marketing in support of game launches. More often the CMO and CRO are the same individual. In large, traditional, 20+ year game companies that have Console, PC and Mobile titles you’ll find both a CMO and a CRO. For mobile game companies you often won’t find a CMO as “brand marketing” is less common for these companies.  
* **Studio General Manager (GM):** The CEO for a specific game studio.  Most responsible for Profit and Loss (P\&L) of the studio as a whole and the games within the studio. Should a game fail and the studio closes the GM will likely take the blame, most definitely be fired along with most of their staff.

**Why Databricks**

* **Data Intelligence Platform:** Most use cases here are focused on making near real time changes to either business operations, or a player’s experience. Having a data platform to simplify this is critical for revenue success in games  
* **Delta Live Tables**: Processes transactions in real time with quality expectations  
* **MLOperations**: Player centric experience requires the derivation of new insight about players through a series of machine learning models. Models like K-Means clustering to find clusters of behavior enable the developer to better market to players and to personalize the player experience.  
* **Unity Catalog**: Provides trust in data with end to end lineage, built in governance and powers our ability to democratize data through solutions like AI/BI.  
* **AI/BI**: Developing models, finding look-a-likes and patterns within player data often requires ad hoc data analysis. Some of this is owned by teams who are data savvy but are not technical in nature. Databricks’ solutions for data and insight democratization are critical here.  
* **Delta Sharing**: Share data with partners, publishers and advertisers in a secure manner without having to move and/or duplicate the data.

## Business Objective: Know Your Player {#business-objective:-know-your-player}

All Player 360 (customer 360\) use cases and requirements fall into this business objective.  While this is the most important objective it is also the most complex, foundational and least exciting of them (e.g. showing an ROI is quite challenging as the net impact is hard to measure).  Without this foundation, however, personalization, dynamic offers, and engagement focused, ML based, activities cannot happen. All engagement, user acquisition and monetization use cases rely on this foundation.

**Here we create foundational insight used across the entire games organization:**

- Creating a unified view of the player that spans multiple games, game studios, games ecosystems and often multiple external CDPs  
- Understanding details of the player and their engagement with the companies titles (games) including:  
  - **Play Sessions**: Play time (how long), which game modes, when do they play  
  - **Efficacy**: How well do they play, win/losses, kill/deaths  
  - **Preferences**: Game modes, in game items, cosmetics, purchase types  
  - **Social details**: Clans, communication, toxicity, chat, linked accounts  
  - **Purchase Propensity**: What do they like to buy, when do they buy, what type of bundles, items vs battle pass (Subscriptions)  
- Enable segmentation and personalization of the game experience for players to improve engagement and retention metrics.

**Why change, why now**  
Nearly all data use cases rely on a solid understanding of a holistic player. Without this foundational effort addressed very few others can be accomplished. This also means that improvements to understanding of a player can benefit all use cases and drive revenue growth when done right.  Waiting will lead to a loss of revenue, a shrinking of their total potential return for a title and potentially the loss of their most dedicated, engaged and profitable players.

Player data is found in a wide variety of data silos created by different lines of business within a game company. As different departments have sought to solve new business problems, or have outsourced different capabilities it has created a wide variety of data silos. With data trapped in these silos, game companies have to make decisions that impact player engagement with incomplete data and insight. This also has the negative effect of making it challenging to link data across these silos ultimately creating duplication of data and an inability to know the player through this signal loss..

By consolidating their player data, multiple CDPs, telemetry data and silos found in other ISV (Independent Software Vendor) solutions game companies can start to improve personalization and player engagement.

**Core Use Cases**

* **Player Metrics**: Understand your players and their relationship with your game holistically to support personalization, marketing, segmentation and other efforts with metrics like Lifetime Value (LTV), retention, First Time User Experience (FTUE) and play sessions.  
* **Churn Mitigation**: Understand and mitigate player churn across the player lifecycle.  
* **Segmentation**: Better understand player behavior to drive more impactful engagement and retention strategies.  
* **Identity Resolution**: Identifying a player across their entire engagement journey from Web, to Ad Targeting, to in game across multiple platforms and multiple titles.

**Key Objectives / KPIs**

* This objective encompasses metrics (KPIs) related to engagement including user counts over time, retention, game sessions, player experience, and player journey.  For more details go to [go/games-kpis](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1saG5waDpXYPhOCaLIBesmdIH66I-PmFFAOFoVTdQUDY/edit?tab=t.0#heading=h.33soo5dsj17n)  
* **Lifetime Value (LTV)**: The lifetime dollar value attributed to an individual player  
* **Retention**: The percentage of users who continue to use the product or service over a specific time period after their initial engagement  
* **Session Length**: The amount of time a user spends interacting with the product or content in a single session

**Key Personas**

* **Executive Leadership**: CEO and Studio Leadership (General Managers), VP of Data (aka Chief Analytics Officer, VP of Player Insights), CTO  
* **Middle Management Domains**: Player Insights, Marketing, LiveOperations  
* **Individual Contributors**: Data Engineers, Product Managers, Behavioral Analyst, Data Scientists

- Databricks simplifies data collection through capabilities like **LakeFlow connect** and **delta sharing**. Our partners ecosystem enables easier ingestion as well through available connectors  
- **Databricks' Unity Catalog** simplifies data governance for critical PII datasets with centralized control, auditability and lineage tracking

**Business Value**

* **Revenue Generation:** Games seek to monetize players while enjoying the experience. In order to maximize that revenue stream they need to personalize the player experience. This requires a deep understanding of the players' habits and desires  
* **Foundational Objective:** Without Player360 no other objectives can be effective.  
* **Player (Customer) Alignment**: Efforts here have an outsized impact to the studios business as it will allow them to better align to the wants and needs of their customers. Within reason, the more data about a player that is used to segment (via heuristics), understand demographics and create cohorts (ML based segmentation) the more accurate the picture and, therefore, the more effective downstream initiatives like: campaign optimization, next best offer, recommendations and personalization will be.

**Common Data Sources**

* **Game Telemetry**: Signals coming out of end user devices like PCs, Consoles and Mobile Devices  
* **BaaS**: Purchase, entitlement and activity within a title that come from SDKs built by third parties or the game company itself  
* **Web Telemetry**: Signals that come from cookies and other web tracking technologies and approaches.  
* **Other ISVs**: Solutions to point needs like chat, video, anti-toxicity and anti-cheat.  
* **UXR (User Research)**: Surveys of players to understand their reaction to the game  
* **Game Engine**: Details about the game binary like version, platform, device type, etc.  
* **Social Signals**: From Discord, Reddit, YouTube, X and similar sources.  
* **Third Party Stores**: The primary source for user reviews  
* **Game Platforms**: Like Playstation, XBox, Steam and Nintendo which provide details about the user’s library, completion rates and trophy completion.

## Business Objective: Grow Your Playerbase {#business-objective:-grow-your-playerbase}

Here we’re focusing on User Acquisition (UA) aka the acquiring of players (generally) through advertising. Games companies can spend between 15% (for AAA/Console/PC game makers) to 43% (mobile) of revenue on advertising. It is not uncommon for a mobile game to spend million(s) per month on advertising.  Even hit games continuously spend to keep attracting new players to the game and backfill for players that have quit. This can come in the form of performance marketing (buying ad space in mobile games and websites) or brand marketing (like TV commercials and billboards). While the most significant portion of the advertising budget is spent at launch, especially for PC/Console games, older games often engage in these practices to inject new players. One example being the Liam Neason commercial that Supercell ran several years after the launch of clash of clans. Mobile games, especially, can be seen to grow their spend on marketing as they succeed. It is said that Monopoly Go’s marketing budget exceeds several hundred million dollars, even though they are bringing in a billion in revenue annually already. The focus is to increase the yield of advertising as, generally speaking, the goal isn’t to spend less on advertising but instead to bring in more players and players more likely to monetize or be big spenders with the budget allocated.

**Helping marketers and user acquisition specialists**:

- **Analyze cohorts of entering players:** Understand the players that came in at a specific time, from a specific ad platform or from a specific advertising campaign  
- **Track the source of new players**: This involves Ads Attribution and the more complex, but critical, multi-touch attribution (most players don’t click on the first ad of yours they see).  
- **Optimize Ad Campaigns**: Where they spend their money, how much money to spend with which ad creatives  
- **Create better ads:** This could involve the generation of ads creative (the visual thing you engage with), or segmenting players based off of metadata from the ads creative.

**Why change, why now**  
Because of changes like ATT, the death of the Cookie, GDPR and the E-Directive it has become increasingly hard for game companies to acquire new users. To comply with these regulations ad providers are giving companies fewer knobs to turn making it hard for them to target the players they are most interested in. Advertising budgets are not increasing, and yields are diminishing. As a result game companies need to be more judicious with their advertising spend allocation. They also need to be able to share look-alike lists with ad networks to help the network place ads in the right places and in front of the right audiences. This is an example of why a solid soft launch approach is important in launching a new game. For new studios, or new games, these lists are produced based off of the performance that is seen during soft launch. After the game launches globally and additional players join the experience, the developer (or publisher) will adjust these lists to align with the current playerbase.

**Core Use Cases**

* **Cohort analysis**:  The analysis of a group of similar people. Within marketing this is most often either based on when the player joined, or which marketing campaign was ultimately responsible for them joining. The purpose of this analysis is to try and optimize different aspects of the business such as ads campaign optimization, ads creative (the art/asset that was used in the marketing campaign) and content releases.  It is important to note that a single player may be part of multiple cohorts.   
* **Ads attribution**: When a player joins: which campaign do I attribute them to? This is used to help determine where to invest marketing dollars  
* **Multi-touch ads attribution**: Most players will see, or engage with, multiple ads before downloading a game. This use case seeks to try and allocate value to the different touchpoints through their acquisition journey.  There is no easy answer here, particularly after cookies were deprecated and with the introduction of ATT.  
* **Ads campaign optimization**: The pursuit of maximizing the output of an ad campaign (e.g. maximize downloads, installs, FTUE and ultimately revenue yielded from advertising spend).

**Key Objectives / KPIs**

* **Return on Ad Spend (ROAS)**: How much money is earned based on marketing budget spent.  
* **Average Revenue per User (ARPU):** This helps to define their marketing budget and ensure that they are yielding more than they’re spending.  
* **Average Revenue Per Paying User (ARPPU):** This helps them to understand how much more valuable spenders are as it eliminates the noise caused by non-paying users  
* **Cost per Mille (CPM)**: Cost per 1,000 impressions of an ad. Not favored as a KPI  
* **Effective Cost Per Mille (eCPM):** This is a term used by ad networks to help game companies understand how much they are spending per 1,000 ad impressions  
* **Cost Per Install (CPI):** For the budget spent how many installs did they get. Knowing this and comparing it across networks, geographies, cohorts and time enables companies to allocate budget more effectively  
* **Click Through Rate (CTR)**: What percentage of users click on an ad when seen. Intended to help understand the effectiveness of the creative being used.

**Key Personas**

* **Executive Leadership**: Chief Marketing Officer, Chief Growth Officer  
* **Middle Management Domains**: Marketing, Marketing Analytics, Business Intelligence  
* **Individual Contributors**: Business Intelligence, Campaign Optimization Analyst

**Databricks Technical Advantage**

- Databricks simplifies processing complex data structures often found in games with higher order functions that help flatten and transform data within SQL or pySpark  
- Databricks simplifies batch and real-time machine learning efforts with integrated capabilities, like **ML Endpoints**, and operational capabilities through our managed **MLFlow** offerings  
- **Databricks AI/BI capabilities** empower non-technical data users to have a conversation with their datasets and produce insight with less help, or work, from central data teams.

***Required Capabilities***

Ads attribution is particularly complex and requires significant estimation. The prediction of lifetime value (LTV) is another ML problem used to help guide marketing spend |
| **DATA SHARING** | To improve the impact of their marketing spend, game companies will provide look-alike lists to their advertising partners. This data sharing needs to remain secure and easy to manage. |

**Business Value**

* **Cost Optimization:** A game company will spend between 17% (Console/PC) and 43% (Mobile) of their revenue on User Acquisition (Marketing). In general they are not looking to spend less money on marketing but, instead, to improve their yield for their marketing dollars. Through these use cases we help them optimize that marketing spend and grow their overall revenue through user acquisition.  
* **Revenue Generation:** Without users a game cannot profit.  By effectively leveraging their marketing partners, marketing campaigns and remarketing efforts they can maximize the number of players that enter their game. 

**Customer Story**

| Zynga's Challenges Scale and Diversity: Building data products for a diverse portfolio of games with billions of events, tens of millions of users, and hundreds of predictive signals. Manual Feature Engineering: Previously required building new models for each game and action, with manual feature engineering for diverse event taxonomies. Computational Limitations: Existing single-machine setups couldn't handle the scale of data generated by games with tens of millions of active users.  Databricks Solution Zynga sought to automate and scale their machine learning processes across their entire game portfolio. They implemented a solution using PySpark, Pandas UDFs, and the Featuretools library on Databricks, creating an end-to-end data product called AutoModel. This system automates feature engineering, scales to tens of millions of users, and generates hundreds of propensity models daily for all games in their portfolio.  Measurable Impact Automated most of the work involved in building propensity models for games. Scaled from processing tens of thousands to tens of millions of users. Generated hundreds of propensity models daily across their entire game portfolio. Enabled data scientists to focus more on improving games with product managers rather than manual model building. Achieved portfolio-scale machine learning, allowing any game in their portfolio to integrate with the data product. |

**Industry Acronyms and Terminology**

* **Golden Cohort**: The first group of players, typically the most valuable cohort. * **Soft Launch**: Launching a title into a subset of available markets to test performance and adjust the game or marketing approach.  
* **(Ads) Creative**: The image, video or playable advertisement that is shown as part of a marketing campaign

## Business Objective: Grow Your Revenue {#business-objective:-grow-your-revenue}

We now know the players that we are bringing in through user acquisition (UA), it’s time to maximize our revenue for the title.  If you’re familiar with the different approaches that are taken within E-Commerce and Retail, this will feel quite familiar to you.

**Here we help revenue analysts, CROs, GMs, etc**:

- **Track spend patterns** and predict revenue over time  
- **Determine the best products to offer** a player based on Know, Grow and their spend patterns  
- **Provide real time product offers** for players  
- **Limit the impact of fraud** on the business from a pure revenue perspective and from the perspective of their key metrics (e.g. removing bots/fraudsters from aggregated figures that could be either depressing the view of the business or overstating the state of the business)

**Why change, why now**  
As the industry has shifted further into the GaaS (Games as a Service, aka Live Service or Free to Play) business model it has caused gamers to play fewer games but for longer periods of time. Gamers simply don’t have sufficient time in the week to play more than 1-3 live service games. With many of these games free to play gamers will download a title and give it 10 minutes to 2 hours to hook them. If they don’t have an excellent experience upfront the user will not only quit but has actually cost the game company money. These costs come in the form of: User Acquisition costs (e.g. what they spent on marketing to get them to play), general operations costs (the data they are now storing, processed, etc) and in game server costs (the servers used for the games matches).  As a side note: not all players in a free to play game will monetize and while it would be nice for them all to do so. For a social game to succeed they need a lot of players.  Some players who do not monetize are, effectively, content for other players to engage with.

As with our consumption business the faster that they find players who will monetize the sooner they can build that revenue stream. Acting faster, finding those players sooner, personalizing their experience and ensuring that they don’t churn has a compounding effect on revenue. 

Finally, new entrants are always coming into the market. Once a player has spent money on a title it is that much harder to get them to switch to yours (e.g. switching cost / can’t bring your stuff with you).  The longer game companies wait to optimize these processes, the less likely they are to succeed.

**Core Use Cases**

* **Recommendation engines**: A program, often an ML model or vector store lookup, that makes a recommendation for a player. While it can apply to many use cases the term generally refers to purchase offers. This can come in the form of an ad to make an MTX purchase, a carousel (short list of items to buy) or the order a game store might show its items.  
* **Next best offer**: Based on the last action, or some form of trigger, what is the next best offer (for purchase) that can be shown to a player to get them to make a purchase.  
* **Personalization**: Efforts made to change the experience of a player to boost engagement or entice a purchase.  
* **Purchase optimization**: The optimization of SKUs, offers and timing of offers.  
* **Fraud analysis/prevention**: Efforts to determine if a transaction is fraudulent, to avoid it occurring again and to eliminate fraudulent transactions from other analysis as it may skew the analysis causing a bad business decision to be made. For example: Imagine a fraudster buys hundreds of a specific hat with the intention to resell it to others and make a profit, you might believe that those hats are suddenly very popular and invest in creating more of them.

**Key Objectives / KPIs**

* **Concurrent Users (CCU)**: How many users are online at any given time? What’s your average? Is that average growing, or shrinking, at what rate? How does your CCU look during an event as compared to baseline? Are there patterns during the day?  
* **Daily Active Users (DAU)**: The number of unique users who engage with the content or product within a 24-hour period.  
* **Average Revenue Per Active Daily User (ARPDAU)**: Take the total revenue for a given period of time, divide it by the number of days and the average daily active user count and you get a feeling for how much money you earn per player each day. There are variants of this KPI that focus on the customer, or per paying user, instead of the user. Ultimately we’re just trying to understand how much revenue we pull in from operations with the goal of understanding how much more we could earn if we had more users, or more paying customers.  
* **Lifetime Value (LTV)**: The total revenue expected for a specific group. There are several variants of this KPI. When expressed as just LTV it is typically a backward looking number based on actual spend.  
* **Predicted Lifetime Value (pLTV)**: Based on the average LTV for a cohort, your total user or customer base, what do we predict the long term value to be.  
* **Customer Lifetime Value (cLTV)**: The same as above but only considering paying players.  
* **Retention (D\#)**: The percentage of players that are still playing after a period of time.  D1 for after day 1, D7 after day 7, etc. Most game studios will measure D1, D7, D30, D90 and D365.   
* **Time to First Transaction**: How long does it take for a player, on average, to convert. Some games will convert quickly and others will take a while. We’ve observed games with this metric measured in days, in a week or two and others where the average time to first transaction was 65 days. While obviously sooner is better, different game genres will bring in different player types. A longer time to the first transaction isn’t a sign of failure but a benchmark for the developer to improve upon.  If today it is 5 days, how do we make it 4? If 60, how to make it 50?  A disadvantage of longer times to first dollar is that it can be challenging to estimate the value of a player early in their experience and to personalize their revenue related experience as a result.

* **Middle Management Domains**: Monetization, Revenue, Fraud  
* **Individual Contributors**: Data Scientists, Business Intelligence, Data Analysts

**Industry Acronyms and Terminology**

* **Games as a Service (GaaS)**: Games where monetization occurs after a player has started playing the game.  
* **Free to Play (F2P)**: As implied, this is games where it is free to download and play the game and all revenue generation occurs after installation  
* **Live Service**: A game where the release of the title is only the beginning and updates to the game are frequent so as to keep players engaged over a long period of time (e.g. years, even decades)  
* **Grinding**: Spending time, on often repetitive or annoying tasks, to gain a resource so as to progress in a game.   
* **Micro Transactions (MTX)**: Purchases made for items or things within a game. Includes cosmetics, subscriptions, battle passes and other (typically) non gameplay impacting purchases.  
* **In App Purchases (IAP)**: Refers to transactions that happen within the game. This term is generally used for mobile games. Can be used interchangeably with MTX.  
* **Virtual Currency**: MTX and IAP are generally used to convert real money into a virtual currency by the game. This enables the developer to quickly modify the real dollar cost of items and provide custom offers. It also has the added impact of obfuscating the purchase decision for the player.  A hat might cost 100 VBucks, or gems. That could be $10 or $25 or $1…at the time of decision the player likely doesn’t really know.  This currency can be purchased but can often also be earned through grinding.  
* **Premium Currency**: The same as virtual currency but can typically only be purchased.  
* **Pay to Win (P2W)**: When an MTX or IAP provides the player an advantage within the game creating a power imbalance between free players and paid players. Generally P2W is bad for a community and is something to be avoided. This is especially the case for PC/Console games. Within mobile gaming it is more common though it is often Pay for Convenience (e.g. I pay to avoid having to grind for something).  
* **Direct to Consumer (D2C):** Efforts made to sell directly to a consumer  
* **Battle Pass (BP)**: A curated journey that includes a series of objectives for the player to accomplish. Has the intention of giving players a reason to come back and play / engage more in the game over a period of time. The time a pass is open is often referred to as a season. While seasons are typically about a month, they can run from 14 days to several months. When implemented there is typically a free BP, a premium and sometimes an ultra premium BP. The purpose of the free BP is to encourage high levels of engagement with the player and to provide FOMO (Fear of Missing Out) for the premium rewards (which are often visible while collecting the free rewards). This has become a very common monetization method for games.  
* **GACHA (Mechanics)**: Game mechanics that are modeled after the Japanese GACHA ball machines where you put money in a machine, and a ball is dropped with an item at random inside it. Items tend to have different rarity creating a desire to keep “playing” until you get the item you wanted.  
* **Loot Boxes:** A form of GACHA mechanic that is displayed as a box full of loot (in game items).   
* **Skinner Boxes**: Referring to the skinner experiments on behavioral conditioning. Mechanics within a game that teach a player that if they do action X they’ll get reward Y. A derogatory term used for generally exploitative mechanics that aren’t really fun but keep a player engaged doing a repetitive task for some form of reward.  
* **Slot Machine Mechanics**: Similar to GACHA or Loot boxes but expressed in a form more similar to that of a slot machine.  Where you are guaranteed to get an item from GACHA or a Loot box, but the quality or rarity is random, in a slot machine mechanic you may get nothing, or may get a jackpot depending on the odds of the machine/game.  
* **Ad Monetization (AdMon)**: Generating revenue by placing ads within your game.  Common in mobile games, especially more casual games.  
* **Rewarded Ads**: An advertisement that a user opts into that provides a reward. Rewards are typically Virtual Currency, are commensurate with the amount of money the developer makes on the ad, but are small enough that they do not negate the desire to make a MTX. This is often an additive revenue stream for games and is only really found in mobile games. Developers are generally concerned that this will cannibalize their MTX revenue but studies (by Google) have shown that they boost revenue as a whole and generally do not replace IAP.  
* Interstitial Ads: An ad forced upon a user to continue the game. Most often used in Hypercasual Games

**Common Data Sources**

* **Game Platforms**: Like Playstation, XBox, Nintendo, Steam.  The places where people purchase the games and transact  
* **App Stores**: Term used for mobile specific transaction platforms like Apple App Store and Google Play  
* **Web Stores**: Off platform stores found on the web. A growing revenue stream, particularly for older games that are trying to squeeze profit from a slowing user base.  XSolla being the greatest example of this.

**Technology Ecosystem**

* **Playstation, XBox, Nintendo**: In platform, console, stores  
* **Steam, Epic Games Store**: Third party PC focused game storefronts  
* **Origin, UPlay+, etc**: Direct to Consumer (D2C) platforms run by the game publishers themselves  
* **XSolla**: Popular webstore provider often used as an alternative to buying through Apple’s App Store or Google Play to increase profit to the developer and enable higher discounting for the consumer.  
* **Apple App Store, Google Play**: Primary Mobile App Stores  
* **IntentHQ**: Databricks built on partner focusing on revenue optimization and personalization

The reality is that most game companies under 300 people and many above that watermark have barely scratched the surface on how to tackle these problems.  These are some of the most critical use cases to a live game but it is hard to prove a causal relationship between effort and outcomes.  With the contention in the industry related to GaaS titles and MTX these are use cases that are often shunned or not talked about by the creative teams.

# Strategic Priority: Build Great Games {#strategic-priority:-build-great-games}

The following focuses on the creation and running of a game (title). Without a product that resonates with players, game companies can’t hope to monetize them. By analyzing their past performance, reviews and that of similar games companies can mitigate their risk in the development process.

Once the game has been released the journey has just begun for many game companies and the games they create. Ensuring effective (live) operations of their title, a safe community in which players can engage, creating new content to keep players happy and fixing bugs, issues and game balance are all critical efforts that are best done when informed by data.

**Why Change**  
Game development cycles and budgets have exploded. We have seen a lot of failed, big budget, games in the last couple of years. A failed title can mean the closing of a business (Concord: Firewalk Studios), the firing of a CEO (Payday 3:  Starbreeze Studios) or the cancellation of future titles. For a game to be successful it must 1\) resonate with a playerbase, 2\) have a “boring launch” and 3\) respond to player wants and needs over time.

By leveraging data from their past releases, public sources, feedback on competitive titles and from their community as they continue the game’s live operations, game companies can de-risk their development and improve the player experience while playing their games.  These data problems require making sense of data from disparate sources and making sense of unstructured data.  This is a great fit for Databricks as a result.

**Why Now**  
For game developers that have titles in flight the sooner they can process these signals and take action the better chance they have to release a successful title.  For developers whose titles are in the market, they are under constant attack from new entrants seeking to acquire their playerbase. For developers starting their journey, or that are contemplating their next title, the decision to make a specific game, target a specific market or playerbase will fundamentally impact their potential for success. Most game companies can’t restart their development cycle without putting their company at risk.

**Business Executives**

* **Chief Executive Officer (CEO)**: Each game is an existential crisis for many game developers. A CEO of a conglomerate might not be on the chopping block for a failed title, but multiple misses could be.  
* **Studio General Manager (GM)**: Most studios do not survive a failed game. If they fail to land there is a good chance that the Studio’s GM will take the blame and will not be around much longer.  
* **Chief Operations Officer (COO)**: Will own the operations of the titles and their risk profile. They’ll be responsible for Cyber security, Cloud Operations and the financial operations of a title once live.  
* **VP Cloud Operations**: Owns the budget for cloud usage and will be seeking data to help with that optimization.  
* **Chief Product/Production Officer (CPO)**: Owns the production of the game itself. The developers, their producers and the likes. This role can carry many titles including Chief Creative Officer.

**Why Databricks**

* **AI/BI**: Game makers are not traditionally data oriented people. They will not have strong SQL skills and will not be able to frame their questions, at least initially, in SQL format. Putting these teams in the drivers seat will enable them to “see” the data and the progression to insight they need to believe it.  
* **Streaming and Delta Live Tables**: Releases and LiveOperations often require near real time decision making. If something is broken  the developer may only have minutes, or hours, to make a change before it has a significant impact on their financial outcomes.

## Business Objective: De-Risk Game Development {#business-objective:-de-risk-game-development}

Players, without a title that players want to engage with, can’t be effectively monetized. Game companies are trying to build better games, faster and aligned with the wants of their playerbase (target player audience). This objective aligns most closely with product managers (who make features for games), game directors and other creators within a game company.

**We help game builders**:

- **Determine what game to make**: by understanding the wants of their players, their feedback, how they have played previous games and what content they are engaging with  
- **Build better games**: by finding patterns, bugs (issues) and feedback uncovered during their play tests  
- **Speed the development process**: with GenerativeAI for the ideation (or creation) of in game assets, localization (translation: language and market needs), and finding issue patterns within the game build process  
- **Balance their games**: by finding patterns within the game that could negatively affect the enjoyment of their playerbase

**Why change, why now**  
More often than not games are made as a result of gut feeling, emotional attachment and the vocal minority. Reliance upon these signals contribute to the boom or bust reality of games. Our target customers and prospects are making decisions that will impact their business for the next decade. Enabling insight that cuts through the above heuristics to help them derisk their business sooner will yield large dividends for them.

**Core Use Cases**

* **Feedback analysis**: Taking in feedback, and comments, from sources like Steam, Platform Reviews, X and Reddit and pulling out insight, at scale, with minimal human intervention. This feedback is then used to inform decisions in the game development process.  
* **Content generation**: A contentious topic within games but something that every company is evaluating today. Creating text, voice, mocap, concept art and 3D assets. The goal is to be more efficient and to get games to market more quickly. The challenge is that this is a creative endeavor and it is viewed as an attempt to pay people less.  
* **Localization**: Often outsourced by developers to third parties. Leveraging ML and GenAI tools developers can limit the need to outsource this work and, instead, do it internally in a more controlled manner that is both faster and cheaper.  
* **Game balance analysis**: As developers seek to improve games that have been released, create additions to existing titles or to release the next version of a title they seek to improve the player experience through changes to the game’s balance.  
* **Game Build Optimization**: Building a game binary is a costly affair from a dollar and time perspective. By finding ways to optimize this process they can speed development and free up budget for other aspects of the project.

**Key Objectives / KPIs**

* **Milestone Completion Rate**: Is the team meeting milestones on time and to the standard expected. This helps with the health of the game but can also impact the revenue for a game developer as publishers (if they’re working with one) may not release funds to the developer if a milestone is not met by a specific date.  
* **Bug Detection and Resolution Rate**: How are bugs located and triaged. At what point in development are the bugs found and what impact do they have on other systems.  
* **Asset Completion Percentage**: Monitoring this KPI can prevent bottlenecks in the production pipeline and help maintain a balanced workflow across different development teams.  
* **Prototype Iteration Time**: Before going into the production phase a game will go through a series of prototypes. The longer they spend in prototyping the more resources are expended by the team as downstream staff will have less work to do.  This is a place where GenAI / Content Generation can be incredibly useful.  
* **Build Time**: How long does a build take to make  
* **Incremental Build**: A build that only compiles files that have changed since the last build, saving time.

**Key Personas**

* **Executive Leadership**: Chief Product Officer, Chief Technology Officer, Game Director, Executive Producer  
* **Middle Management Domains**: Product Management, UXR (User Experience Research), Game Development  
* **Individual Contributors**: Game Developer, Gameplay Analyst, Gameplay Engineer, Product Manager, Associate Producer

**Competitive Intelligence**  
This is generally a blue sky opportunity. With Databricks we are seeking to uncover patterns that can be used to improve the processes as a whole. In one example a game studio noticed that builds submitted after 3pm on Fridays were much more likely to have bugs introduced. They theorized that people were trying to submit before the weekend came and the result was less rigorous testing and validation before committing code. As a result they stopped all but essential build requests after noon on Friday and clarified with the team that they’d rather a build wait till Monday then be rushed out the door. These changes resulted in an increase in code quality and a decrease in overall bugs for the project.

## Business Objective: Effective Live Operations {#business-objective:-effective-live-operations}

A large number of games these days are Live Games.  A Live Game is one where content is continuously created for the title with the hope to keep players playing indefinitely and to monetize them during their engagement with the title. Sometimes referred to as GaaS (Games as a Service) or LiveOps (LiveOperations) these games can be incredibly profitable, if successful. The most commonly thought of titles in this category include: World of Warcraft (WoW), Grand Theft Auto (GTA), Fortnite and Minecraft.  The juggernauts listed make it challenging for new entrants to find success and we’ve seen a lot of failed attempts in the market. The Live Games that succeed are ones that leverage their data to maximize the fun while appropriately monetizing their players.

**We help game builders**:

- **Understand**: the current state of the game, of players, the impact of recent content drops (releases)  
- **(AB) Test**: new content, personalization attempts and changes to the game  
- **Create**: new content for the title. Or these games to succeed a constant supply of frequent content drops is required. The most successful titles will release content weekly or, at a minimum, monthly.  
- **Support their community**: by identifying and responding to issues as they arise within the title be it bugs, issues with other players or content that isn’t resonating with the community  
- **Protect their players**: from fraud, abuse, toxic/disruptive players, cheaters, coercion, predators and other negative experiences.  
- **Protect their game**: from security threats, server attacks and theft.  
- **Evolve their game:** as a result of the above

**Why change, why now**  
For most games the first 1-3 months after global release are the most successful of the title. While they will continue to acquire customers and bring new ones in through organic growth they will have already peaked.  Acquiring users is very expensive.  Once a player engages the company has to maximize the value derived from the player.  Just as there is compounding benefit, long term, from taking action sooner, there is compounding detriment when action is delayed. A churned user is, for the most part, gone and they will have to acquire someone to replace them, at great cost.

In addition to the above there are new entrants continuously coming to market and the allure of older games with large, established audiences. It is not hyperbole to say that every month is an existential crisis for a live game, these companies can not sit on their laurels.

Meaningful data projects and integration of insight into game experiences takes time, sometimes considerable time.  Often creative assets, game modes, or fundamental changes to a game have to be made.  Not only does it take time to build these, but a studio may want/need to wait till the next content release to integrate these changes. 

You may ask: Why don’t they just continuously change the game as they find improvements, it is just code, it is online, they could do that, right? Whenever a change is made users have to download large patches to address small changes. The latest Diablo is around 90GB. When they make a release, or find a bug that requires fixing, users will have to download 20, 30 or the whole 90GB. With one million players, at 4c a GB in networking costs, a significant update could cost a game company millions of dollars (1M \* 0.04 \* 90GB \= 3.6M). There’s also frustration with the users from frequent updates.  If a player has only 1 hour to play, but they have to wait 30 minutes for an update, they will often play something different.

Put this all together and you can see how ensuring these updates are effective and thoughtful is so important for a game.

**Core Use Cases**

* **A/B testing**: Before releasing a major, or minor, change to a feature, or aspect of a game, companies will test it within their user group. Databricks may inform who is included in the testing groups through clustering techniques, but is most used during and after an A/B test.  During the test streaming data is important in case there is a breaking change that needs to be discovered and addressed quickly.  After the A/B test evaluation is required. This will include dashboards, KPI comparisons but also exploratory analytic efforts. For this reason AI/BI genie can be especially useful after an A/B test.  
* **Anti-Toxicity**: Studies show that players are 37% more likely to not play a game a second time (churn) if they experience toxicity in their first playthrough. While the churn impact drops after the first session, toxic players are still one of the leading causes of churn. Toxicity is challenging to address because it comes in many forms: verbal harassment, text, berating, griefing and other forms of disruptive play.  For a global game where players may be speaking any number of languages, or using different forms of gamer shorthand (like l33t speak) it is quite challenging to address. Here we leverage ML models to translate to a common language for enforcement, and rely on streaming data pipelines to try and find toxic players before they poison an audience.  
* **Anti-cheat**: Cheating is another form of disruptive play that negatively impacts the games community. As with most cybersecurity threats, cheating is a game of whackamole. New methods of cheating, exploits and tools are constantly being released or improved to try and circumvent the tools intended to stop them. To combat cheating large volumes of data are required to be analyzed. Most of that data, however, is noise. As a result data pipelines have to focus on changes to the incoming data and seek out anomalous behavior. While these workloads will ingest streaming data, as it is produced in real time, the analysis and review process is often done in batch.  
* **Community support**: Medium and large sized games will have hundreds of thousands, if not millions, of players. Players are often passionate about the game they are playing, which means when something isn’t going right they can be very vocal. Communities don’t always express their frustration, or concerns, through the customer support portal either, so game companies have to keep track of feedback wherever it might arise. To help with this use case game companies will leverage chat bots to handle L1/L2 support needs, will ingest review information from places like Steam to track community sentiment across the population and may scrape social media like Discord, Reddit and X.  With so many inbound signals it is impossible for humans to review all feedback, comments and respond. Here we leverage capabilities like LLMs to help summarize and find patterns across these datasets.  
* **Child Safety and Anti-Grooming**: A challenging use case to talk about and to consider but one that is real and a focus for the industry. UGC (User Generated Content) platforms like Roblox have been most targeted by these predators as a high proportion of users are under the age of 13\. Detecting grooming and predatory efforts is very difficult as individual interactions tend to appear benign, tracking conversations over a longer period of time is challenging and oftentimes conversations may begin in the game but then move into Discord, WhatsApp, Signal or other third party social platforms.  Once the conversation has left the game the developers have no way to detect or intervene. There’s often a perceived risk by the developers as well who worry that a mistake made by them will make them liable.  As a result of all of this many developers choose to outsource these functions to third parties. 

**Key Objectives / KPIs**

* **Server Uptime**: What percentage of the time are servers up, running and accepting matches  
* **Server Related Game Disconnect**: How often do matches fail as a result of a backend technical issue.  
* **Net Promoter Score (NPS)**: How satisfied are players with the game in its current state. Not used as much as other metrics. Is often focused on the brand image vs the state of play.  
* **(Steam) Review Score**: What percentage of players are happy with the title as measured by reviews on platforms like Steam. This score changes over time and game companies often will compare the score of their current release vs their past release and vs all time to spot trends, change over time and the impact of releases on the games’ success within the eyes of their players.  
* **Outstanding support tickets**: How many tickets are still outstanding  
* **Mean time to support resolution**: How long does it take to respond to issues reported by players.  
* **Time to Ban**: For a player that is ultimately banned due to cheating or toxicity, how long did it take to identify that behavior after it was first observed.  
* **Toxicity Population**: What percentage of the games population is toxic or playing in a disruptive manner

* **Middle Management Domains**: Live Operations, Revenue, Content Development, Cloud/Server Management  
* **Individual Contributors**: Community Support, Anti-Cheat / Security, LiveOperations Analyst, LiveOperations Content Developer, Server Engineer, Technical Director

**Business Value**

* **Revenue**: For players to consistently spend on in game purchases they need a positive play experience. This is true from Quality of Service (e.g. server uptime and latency), a customer support lens and the community as a whole (e.g. is the community toxic). To maximize revenue the game company has to ensure a positive player experience.  
* **Cost Optimization**: Live Games (e.g. multiplayer and online games that seek to monetize players during their experience) are very expensive to run. The cloud spend for a live game is typically between 8-13% of revenue. The cloud costs for running a live game is often one of the largest line items for their operating costs. Game companies will leverage analytics to understand the impact of that investment and to find efficiencies that can lower their cost structure.

**Industry Acronyms and Terminology**

* **The Ban Hammer**: A term used to refer to the most commonly used deterrent to cheating and toxicity: banishment. This is when a player is no longer allowed to play the game, their user name has been locked out of the experience. Bans can be temporary (e.g. 1-7 days) or permanent. They are not an ideal solution, however. A banned player may create a new username and start the cycle all over. Knowing they might be banned again they are less likely to spend money on the game and are now a drain on the resources of the company. Finding these new accounts is a challenge as typical identifiers (IP address or MAC address for example) can be spoofed (faked) or be routed through a VPN to mask their identity. It is also possible that the toxic, or cheating, player may be a streamer with a heavy following (which banning could cause backlash) or a whale (highly monetizing player). While challenging, starting a conversation with these players to try and change their behavior is a step that needs to be taken. RAG and LLM based chatbots can be effective here.  
* **Cheater’s Island**: An alternative employed by some companies as an alternative to banishment.  Cheaters are put onto servers (islands) with other cheaters, often without the knowledge of the player.  Eventually the player will realize that they’re playing exclusively with cheaters and may churn out but in the interim you’ve had a chance to see more cheating behavior for you to learn and grow from.   
* **Griefing**: Generally speaking, playing in such a way that negatively impacts the experience of others. Technically speaking the use of an exploit or bug to negatively impact the play experience of another.  
* **Disruptive Play**: Playing, or acting, in such a way that negatively impacts the experience of others. This can include verbal or chat toxicity. It can also include bullying within a game. Finally it also includes playstyles that are viewed as negative such as camping, door blocking and cheesing.  
* **User Generated Content (UGC)**: Content that is created by the end user, the player or a creator on a platform. Platforms like Roblox, Minecraft, RecRoom, Unreal Engine for Fortnite and Manticore are the most well known platforms.  These platforms are often referred to as the metaverse.  
* **l33t speak**: L33t speak is a stylized online writing system replacing letters with numbers and symbols. It originated in 1980s hacker culture and became popular in gaming communities, used for avoiding detection or as playful expression.   
* **Cheesing**: Doing things in such a way that might make for a good meme video but is generally funny at the expense of someone else.  
* **Child Safety and Abuse Material (CSAM)**: Images or videos that depict the abuse of children or seek to mimic the abuse of children. These can be real content or generated content.   
* **National Center for Missing and Exploited Children (NCMEC)**: A non-government organization (NGO) that seeks to help stop the abuse of children and bring children who may be subject to abuse back to safety.

**Common Data Sources**

* **Game engine telemetry**: data coming out of the game engine about the game itself including actions by the player, movement, game build details and other identifiers about the game being played.  
* **Third party anti-cheat software**: Software that seeks to outsource the discovery of cheaters in games.  
* **Networking telemetry**: Binary data coming out of the game and streaming to the game server.   
* **Game and Match Details**: Outcomes from matches and other details about the player’s engagement with the game.  This data is used to help find anomalous outcomes and activities within a game.  
* **Text and voice chat solutions or providers**: Game companies will often outsource text and voice capabilities to third parties like Vivox and Agora. It’s important to know that, oftentimes, players will use Discord instead of the capabilities used within the game itself.  More often than not game companies have no visibility into what may be said, or done, within communication channels like discord.

# **Strategic Priority: Ensure Efficient Business Operations** {#strategic-priority:-ensure-efficient-business-operations}

This is a catch all encompassing the complexity of running a games organization. These companies, especially once they’ve hit 300+ people, tend to be highly complex, internally competitive and a series of subsidiaries generally working towards mutual success. IT and HR use cases fall into this category but are not enumerated below as they are not unique to this industry. Most of these use cases are unique to larger game companies.

**Why Change**  
Game budgets have exploded to a level that seems unsustainable and there’s no guaranteed formula for success. Game companies have vast amounts of data available to them, but enabling all lines of business (from Marketing, Revenue, Operations and Game Development) to leverage this data has proven challenging. As a creative endeavor, game developers often do not believe the data they are provided and make decisions based on their gut feelings and not the data they are presented.

As a whole this has led to a belief that the industry isn’t optimizing its resources well and is taking unnecessary risks. Several large companies have recently failed, or been acquired to stay afloat and it would appear that no developer is safe.

**Why Now**  
Most game developers are in the process of building a new title and/or juggling a series of live titles. They are in the process of making decisions that will make or break their company. With a constant stream of new entrants in the market they can’t afford to skip a beat. With additional sinks for players time (like streaming/on-demand video) game companies have a larger group of competitors to consider.

While these challenges are not especially new, there are new solutions and capabilities to attempt to derisk their business. If they do not take advantage of them now, they could be out of business tomorrow.

**Business Executives**

* **Chief Executive Officer (CEO)**: The CEO will be determining how to allocate their resources across a series of games and other business opportunities. They need access to the right data and to be able to trust that data to either inform their decisions or to help them evaluate the efficacy of their gut feelings.  
* **Studio General Manager (GM)**: As the CEO for the studio it is their responsibility to allocate resources within the studio.  They will make the decision on which titles to invest in, and which to divest from. Being able to investigate the data presented to them to make the decisions they make is critical to their success.  
* **(Executive) Producer**: Consider them the CEO for a specific game. They are responsible for the title coming to market on time and on budget. They need to be able to distill vast amounts of HR, Finance and Engagement data to ensure the success of the title.  
* **Chief Operations Officer (COO)**: In addition to backend operations they will often own compliance with different regulations (assuming the organization isn’t large enough to have a Chief Compliance Officer) that regulate their titles including COPPA, GDPR and E-Directive.  See our industry fundamentals course for details on these regulations.  
* **Chief Data Officer (CDO)**: Or the VP of Data, will own ensuring that different teams have access to the right data in a governed and secure manner when they need it.

**Why Databricks**

* **AI/BI**: Enabling all lines of business and the above executives to gain access to insight that would otherwise be locked to them, or would take too long to access.  
* **Unity Catalog**: Ensuring the governance and security of data access.  
* **Data Lineage**: Provided by UC to help ensure trust in the data that is used for decisions  
* **System Tables**: Enabling auditing of data access and its controls

## Business Objective: Optimize Your Operations {#business-objective:-optimize-your-operations}

Databricks helps address the complexity found as a result of larger game companies being closer to conglomerates than being a cohesive company.

**We help teams within central organizations**:

- **Report to the street**: by addressing quality, and enabling standardized aggregation across data silos and teams who may use non-standard KPI definitions  
- **Share data across the organization**: in a governed, secure and manageable manner.  
- **Prepare for strategic initiatives**: by ensuring data quality, trust in that data and the ability to find answers needed to make business decisions quickly.

**Why change, why now**  
The regulatory market is continuously evolving. Being nimble and able to adjust as changes occur will ensure the long term viability of the organization.

Beyond the avoidance of fines there’s also the immediacy and long term impact of decisions made with incomplete or incorrect data, or decision making made without data at all.

**Core Use Cases**

* **Data Sharing**: Game developers need to share data with external entities (like game publishers, game platforms and regulators). They also need to be able to safely share data across their lines of business, or different game studios. A conglomerate might have multiple game studios where they’d like to share insight about players in aggregate but may not be able to share PII data, or can only do so if a user has opted in. This sharing of data may be subject to audit and scrutiny as well.  
* **Clean Rooms**: In the case of sharing data externally a clean room may be necessary.  A game company may wish to share insight about a group of players with vendors like AdMonetization or User Acquisition providers. This could enable them to get more revenue for the players they have or to optimize their User Acquisition / Marketing budget.  
* **Strategic Programs**: A catch all term used to describe large projects that will have a large impact on the company. This could include moving into a new game genre, M\&A or divestiture of a part of the business. These projects generally require a lot of ad hoc analysis and data investigation that AI/BI (Genie Spaces) can assist with.

**Key Objectives / KPIs**

* **Content investment ROI:** Using data to make better decisions on what content to build or add to games to drive the best engagement & returns, while minimizing waste on ‘guess & check’/’spray and pray’  
* **People time lost on data merger:** Today a lot of the merging and checking of data is very manual, occupying a lot of people time (including executives) which siphons this away from making & acting on decisions  
* **Reducing CAC:** By better merging/sharing data across the organization, it becomes easier to more effectively & efficiently target existing customers across the companies ecosystem for their new titles, reducing overall CAC  
* **M\&A Consideration:** Gaming is going through a consolidation at the top end of the market, with a focus on leveraging cross functional assets like marketing & marketplace presence to drive efficiency  
* **Divestiture:** Similarly, gaming is a cut-throat business, so business units & games that are underperforming are often shut down or spun off (called divestiture)

**Key Personas**

* **Executive Leadership**: Chief Data Officer (VP of Data), VP Analytics, Chief Information Officer, VP or Director of Data Engineering  
* **Middle Management Domains**: IT, Business Intelligence, Governance  
* **Individual Contributors**: Data Analyst, IT Operations, Cloud Operations, Data Engineering

## Business Objective: Democratize Your Data {#business-objective:-democratize-your-data}

As most successful game companies have been built over the years through M\&A (mergers and acquisitions) they are plagued with data silos. Each studio may have created their own data platform, game teams may have deviated from the standards provided to them, data is found everywhere. In addition to this you have a wide variety of data consumers from the highly technical to fully non-technical (but that want deep insight).

**We help all teams within a games organization, especially non-core data people:**

- **Find data**: wherever it might be, or consolidated into one platform, and make it discoverable  
- **Turn data into insight**: by enabling all members of the organization to find interesting insight without needing to ask central data teams for assistance  
- **Have a conversation with their data**: so they can help uncover new insight, understand the details behind their insight and provide an opportunity for self service analytics

**Why change, why now**  
In order to stay competitive all lines of business within a game company must have near real time access to data insight and do so in a regulatory compliant manner. Game budgets and the time it takes to make a game have exploded to the point that each title is critical for the ongoing success of a company, regardless of size. Where an expensive game may have cost $100M 5-10 years ago, budgets now exceed $500M regularly. These costs come in the form of development (30-65% of cost) and user acquisition or brand marketing (35-70%).

As interest rates have risen investors have become more shrewd with their money. They are less open to risk and expect higher, guaranteed, returns. Where a game developer may have been able to point to past performance as proof that they were the right investment, investors are requiring more detailed analysis of the market and proposed product.

**Core Use Cases**

* **Data Democratization**: The core use case for this priority. Game developers recognize that they need to make data available to a wider variety of teams to help ensure their success. Creative teams, narrative designers, producers and other parts of the game production pipeline need access but do not have traditional data skillsets. To assist with this use case we bring AI/BI to the table.   
* **Data Governance**: While game developers recognize the need to democratize data they are also concerned about the potential for data leakage or misuse. The games that are in the pipeline, when they’ll release and the market they’ll serve are closely guarded secrets. The release of information before intended can negatively impact a project by: deflating the expectations of their future players, taking the wind out of a planned announcement and providing competitors a chance to beat them to the punch. Take the recent leaks from GTA6 as an example. The footage leaked was quite old and caused great scrutiny and concerns about the project. Instead of impressing the world with the stunning visuals and gameplay they were building, the world saw an old build that was janky and seemed a step back from GTA5. A mistake like this can drop total revenue expectations for the life of a title. 

**Key Objectives / KPIs**

* **Data Security**: Ensuring that data isn’t leaked: whether that be about a project or PII.  
* **Time to Insight**: How much time does the team need to get to the answers they’re looking for. By shortening this time the studio can either increase the speed of development, or operate with fewer resources providing more time for development.

**Key Personas**

* **Executive Leadership**: Chief Data Officer or VP of Data, Director of Data Engineering, CTO  
* **Middle Management Domains**: Business Intelligence, Data Engineering  
* **Individual Contributors**: BI or Data Analyst, Data Engineer

**Databricks Technical Advantage**

- **Databricks AI/BI capabilities** empower non-technical data users to have a conversation with their datasets and produce insight with less help, or work, from central data teams.  
- **Databricks' Unity Catalog** simplifies data governance for critical PII datasets with centralized control, auditability and lineage tracking enabling compliance with regulations like GDPR and CCPA.  
- **Databricks Apps** enables developers to quickly build, deploy, and manage secure data and AI applications eliminating the need for separate infrastructure management.

***Required Capabilities***

**Business Value**

* **Compliance:** Sharing data within an organization or with external partners is tricky. It is difficult to ensure that GDPR, PII and other regulations are followed while granting greater access to data across your organization. Data governance is critical as a result  
* **Revenue:** Once compliance has been addressed and different lines of business are able to develop their own insight you unlock faster reactions to the market, its changes and the changing desires of your players. Being able to do all of this will increase revenue yield.  
* **Cost Optimization**: Similar to revenue, enabling additional lines of business to engage with your data will enable them to find more opportunities for cost optimization.  You also can limit the HC growth needed within data organizations while still growing your business.
